I made up a 'rule of thirds' when printing modulated source content. Either limit your processing chain to 1/3rd of what you'd normally use - or triple the amount of processing to (hopefully) generate something new and unique. Results may vary!

Wake up?
You shake off the haze. The barkeep casting shadow over you.
'Get out. Let it get you.'
Sluggishly you make your way to the door. The locals stare.
Uncertainty painted across their faces
You leave. The door bolts behind you.
Outside.
Midnight.
All feels abandoned aside from sparse lamplight flickering in the rainfall
'Harrowers' the sign above the door reads in the faint glow.
You start walking East through main street.
Any hum you were used to begins to dull.
You cross buildings as you walk in the cobbled street. There is no decoration.
A sign is placed by the door of another pub.
Read sign?
column2: You keep walking. Light is dissipating.

column1: It hasn't stopped raining since your arrival
You keep moving.
Concrete becomes mud as you continue Eastward.
Through the trees.
There is something rustling nearby
You continue. Dead greenery beneath your feet.
There is a small clearing.
The rustling is close.
Look?
There is something in the mud.
column2: Mud is thickening. It feels like pulling.

column1: Squelching.
Writhing.
Wasting.

column2: You try to see through the final wall of dying trees
Struggling. The mud is holding you.
